metadata.name: Happenings #24
metadata.description:
Inspired by the chaos and imperfectly beautiful dynamics of parenting and life, 'Happenings' is the embodiment of the messiness, the unexpected and playful experiences that allow for the greatest depths of connection with our children.

Our intention was to evoke our deepest and most personal feelings as parents of young ones navigating the challenges of the pandemic while immersing ourselves in the Web3 arena.

This collection is Jimena + Marcos‚Äô first generative art collection in the Tezos blockchain via FX Hash, and consists of 222 1/1 artworks created with javascript.

metadata.name: a working theory #83
metadata.description:
Initial conditions are stated, and then the particles set in motion - the root of generative art. My goal with this piece was to create an illustration that seemed to be from an earlier (or perhaps later?) time; not, at any rate, our current moment. The background is a very subtle gradient; then it is heavily stippled, and followed with a particle system to create more subtle texture. (Look for the very small "hairs" in the background; they are more obvious on the dark ones. They are a subset of the main particle system.) 

Following that, the main particle system is run in real time; I like to "show my work" for generative pieces, as any collector of my previous mints knows, and this is no exception. "Run" your mint for an animated drawing experience. Note that fxpreview() hits a few frames before the end of the full run. I did it this way to ensure a consistent preview. As a result, the preview and the final image will be slightly different, only because the final image has a slightly longer lifespan. 

There are multiple "special" modes, each with a 10% likelihood: 

"spiral" will rotate the canvas as the particle system is running.
"chaos" uses random X/Y vectors during the acceleration phase, rather than X or Y.
"occasionals" adds random large particles in an opposing color.

In addition, there are three possible shapes:

"circle" draws circles for the particles.
"square" draws squares for the particles.
"jagged" draws mostly circles, with a 0.01% chance of a square at a 45 degree angle. 

Finally, there is a non-attribute feature, where the entire piece is drawn at a 45 degree angle. This has a 20% likelihood, but is only apparent on pieces that have no special, or the "occasional" special. Working the math out, you have a 16% likelihood for getting a piece at a noticeable 45 degree angle. 

All main colors have an equal likelihood, but the light background is only 20%.

metadata.name: an abstract concept #114
metadata.description:
I often try to duplicate my IRL analog abstract painting in code, and this, like my previous mint "a fleeting moment," is an attempt at that. Or it started that way. As is usual with such things, it quickly took on a life of its own. 

The algorithm itself consists of three layers of the main particle abstraction, which comes in five different styles, and roughly eight layers of the "texture," which comes in three styles. The palette consists of the background color and three colors for the particle algorithm. The texture is always drawn with the first of those three colors (the "base" color.) 

The result is indicative of my normal painting style (I almost always use three color layers over a background color, and paint with a spatula, palette knife, or cake knife) but is its own unique look.

metadata.name: A Forgotten Landscape #23
Ghrian #57
metadata.description:
Dutch auction (13/11/9/6/3), with price decreasing every 10 minutes after the start of the auction until 9 tez. Price will then decrease to 6 tez after 2 hours, then to 3 after 12 hours.

A selection of 33 different palettes.

The brush draw is determined by angles, shapes, randomly chosen overdraws, brush sizes and widths, among other things.

- Left arrow = draw in 2125x1375
- Right arrow = draw in 11x17 landscape mode fit to screen height
- Up arrow = draw in 1375x2125
- Down arrow = draw in 11x17 portrait mode fit to screen width
- Enter = draw in full window
- Tab = draw in 1400x1400
- Shift = draw in 1:1 aspect ratio scaled to window height with 5% border on all sides
- Alt = draw in 1:1 aspect ratio scaled to window height with 5% border on all sides (default pixel density)
- Left mouse click = save as a png

Pixel density is set to 2 for all of the options above unless noted otherwise.

Please note that the drawing can take quite a while to run, especially in the full screen modes.

See thread below for additional details:

https://twitter.com/AndwerEric/status/1492619586931413000?s=20&t=N8joIBuTNzYYjmcBex0QJQ

metadata.name: Nounfall #62
metadata.description:
Nounfall is drawn exclusively from the 234 heads and 21 glasses that are used to build the current Nouns collection. The background colors are all pulled from the blessed Noun palette.

This is ok because Nouns are CC0, which basically means public domain. Check out nouns.wtf for more info.

They make for fun social media banners when cropped, if you wanna show off you fandom of Nouns.

C : Clear screen and start animation over
S : Save current image
1 -> 6 : Set pixel density to the respective number

So, if you want a high resolution file, tap `6` for it to redraw, and then `S` to save. You can also save while it's animating if you like, which is fun too.
